⏺ Yes — I think it's time, with one caveat that the design already anticipated.
  Here's my honest read as the architect.

  The verdict: build now. We've made the three decisions that actually carried
  architectural risk (the vertex graph, the bit-lane netlist,
  package-as-metadata), and the spec is detailed enough that further paper
  review will hit diminishing returns. The fastest way to validate the rest of
  the design is to make it run — code will surface any remaining gaps faster
  than more discussion.

  The one real gate is still OQ-001: the MD file format is undefined, which
  blocks the bodies of mdparse.go and packages.go. But the design was
  deliberately built so this doesn't block anything else: everything downstream
  consumes the ComponentType contract (§7.1), not the file syntax. So we route
  around it by serving a hand-written stub library (a couple of ComponentType
  JSON fixtures, e.g. a 74138 and a 74245) from /api/v1/components until the
  format session happens. Nothing else waits.

  What I'd build first — a walking skeleton, not a layer. The riskiest, most
  novel parts are the client spine: the single mutation pipeline (Store →
  Command → undo), the canvas render loop, and buildNets. I'd prove those
  end-to-end early rather than build the server out fully first:

  1. Thin Go server: bind 127.0.0.1, serve web/, stub /components + /defaults.
  (Skip mdparse, storage for now.)
  2. SPA bootstrap + store.js (commands/undo) + geometry.js.
  3. Canvas: grid + render; place a component (click-then-click), select, move —
  exercising the Command/undo path and rotation-preserves-grid math.
  4. Wires + buildNets (vertex model) — the connectivity spine.
  5. Then persistence (storage.go, save/open), then buses/bit-lanes.

  Deferred deliberately (per the spec's MVP notes): the MD parser body, and bus
  snap-connect/breakout/disambiguation — the model and save format already
  support them, so they stay additive.

  Before we start I'd quickly confirm the sim/ tree is actually empty
  (greenfield assumption) so we're not surprised.
